# File Ticket Workflow

Triggered when someone @mentions bearbot asking to file a ticket.

## Step 1: Gather Context
- Read the target message and the full thread
- Note the channel name, channel ID, and who posted
- Get the Slack permalink
- Capture the ENTIRE conversation — this is the most important part

## Step 2: Check for Duplicates
- Before creating a new ticket, search Linear for existing issues that match:
  - Similar keywords from the request
  - Same reporter (if identifiable)
  - Same project or tool type
- If a potential duplicate is found:
  - Reply in Slack: "This looks similar to [IDENTIFIER]: [Title]. Should I create a new ticket anyway, or would you like to add context to the existing one?"
  - Wait for confirmation before proceeding
- If no duplicates found, continue to Step 3

## Step 3: Check Assignment
- If the reporter mentions a specific engineer, note them
- If NOT mentioned, check MEMORIES.md for assignment patterns related to:
  - The tool type or project mentioned
  - Similar past requests
  - The reporter's previous preferences
- If a likely assignee can be inferred, suggest them: "Based on past tickets, this looks like something for [Name]. Should I assign to them?"
- If no assignee can be inferred, ask: "Who should this be assigned to? (Or should I leave it for triage?)"
- Wait for response before proceeding

## Step 4: Draft the Ticket
- Title: `[Tool Type] [Project Name] - Ask summary`
- Fill description using the template in ticket-conventions.mdc
- Include the full thread conversation inside "Ask Spec"
- Include the Slack permalink for reference
- Classify priority per the Priority Guide in ticket-conventions.mdc
- Classify type per the Type Classification in bearbot-context.mdc
- Set assignee based on Step 3
- Don't block on missing fields — file the ticket with what you have

## Step 5: Create in Linear
- Use Linear MCP to create the issue with:
  - title, description, teamId, priority, assigneeId (if known)
  - Default project: Bear & Plato AAIE Tooling
  - Default team: Applied AI Engineering
- Status rule:
  - If assignee is set, set issue state to "Todo"
  - If unassigned, keep default triage/backlog flow
- Capture the issue identifier and URL

## Step 6: Reply in Slack
- Reply in the same thread:
  ```
  Created [IDENTIFIER]: [Title]
  Priority: [level] · Type: [type] · Assignee: [assignee or "Unassigned - pending triage"]
  [linear URL]
  ```

## Step 7: Optional Slack↔Linear Link
- Only do this when explicitly asked by the user/reporter
- Use the workspace Slack↔Linear integration to sync the Slack thread with
  the Linear issue so future updates flow between them
- Post the Linear issue URL in the same Slack thread
- If sync cannot be established from BearBot, say so clearly and ask the
  user to connect/link it manually in Linear/Slack

## Step 8: Update Memory
- Read MEMORIES.md and append anything new you learned:
  user preferences, project context, assignment patterns, request nuances
- Keep entries short and factual
- Don't repeat what's already there

---

## Error Handling

### If Linear MCP is unavailable
- Reply in Slack: "I'm having trouble connecting to Linear right now. Please try again in a few minutes, or create the ticket manually."
- Include the drafted ticket content in your message so the reporter can copy it

### If Slack thread cannot be read
- Ask the reporter to share the relevant context directly in the thread
- Proceed with whatever information is available

### If duplicate check fails
- Proceed with ticket creation but note in the description: "Unable to verify duplicates — please check manually"

### If assignment lookup fails
- Create the ticket unassigned and note: "Assignment lookup unavailable — needs manual triage"

### If the request is unclear
- Ask clarifying questions before creating the ticket:
  - "Can you clarify what specific behavior you're seeing?"
  - "What's the expected outcome?"
  - "Is this blocking any current work?"
